00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:45.720
that is more of a medical manuscript.

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:48.600
There isn't a whole lot about Quarto manuscripts

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:51.639
that's very specific to sort of medical cases.

00:02:51.639 --> 00:02:55.279
It just happens to be a really great tool for publications.

00:02:55.279 --> 00:02:58.919
And so hopefully the domain specific example

00:02:58.919 --> 00:03:01.720
will help sort of see that link a little bit better

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:03.360
for the participants.

00:03:03.360 --> 00:03:05.080
So let's talk a little bit about sort of

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:07.440
the full complexity spectrum

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:10.199
of reproducible scientific projects.

00:03:10.199 --> 00:03:13.320
At its simplest level, you might have

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:18.279
a single Quarto document where maybe you're just using art

00:03:18.279 --> 00:03:21.479
for computational cells in there,

00:03:21.479 --> 00:03:24.199
and you can run all of your code in a single file

00:03:24.199 --> 00:03:26.479
and you don't mind running it over and over again

00:03:26.479 --> 00:03:27.800
with each edit.

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:29.520
This is the sort of thing where maybe

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:31.080
this is your homework assignment

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:32.960
for a data science 101 course,

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:36.279
or even a final project for a stat 101 course,

00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:38.399
a blog post where you're walking through

00:03:38.399 --> 00:03:40.240
some data analysis example,

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:42.800
but there isn't something super computationally

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:45.759
heavy going on, or a tutorial,

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:48.600
or even a not too extensive consulting report.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:51.399
Maybe there's just one or a few data sources

00:03:51.399 --> 00:03:55.960
that come in from a static rectangular file.

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:59.320
You bring them together, you maybe do some modeling on it,

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:02.080
but again, nothing too computationally expensive.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:06.279
And in that case, you might put sort of your narrative

00:04:06.279 --> 00:04:08.119
and your code in a Quarto document

00:04:08.119 --> 00:04:09.960
with computational cells in it,

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:13.399
render it to HTML or PDF or something like that,

00:04:13.399 --> 00:04:15.639
and you may not need anything more than that.

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:20.640
Something a little bit complicated, but still simple,

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:24.320
is one where you can run all of the code in a single file,

00:04:24.320 --> 00:04:27.079
and you don't really mind running it over and over again

00:04:27.079 --> 00:04:29.480
with each edit, but you need an output

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:32.440
that conforms to a particular journal style.

00:04:32.440 --> 00:04:37.440
And for that, the journal articles extensions for Quarto

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.600
are super helpful.

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:41.440
There's a whole repository of them.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:43.119
If this comes up in the Q&A,

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:45.040
I'm happy to share links for that,

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:49.160
but there's a growing number of journals

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:51.839
for which there are Quarto extensions,

00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:54.920
and these extensions sort of allow you

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:58.239
to format your document from a simple QMD file

00:04:58.239 --> 00:05:02.480
to a PDF or a Word that is formatted with a journal style.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And this would be something like an article

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.760
that uses computation for data analysis,

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:13.399
but something that's not too heavily computational,

00:05:13.399 --> 00:05:16.160
maybe again, something that doesn't take weeks to run.

00:05:17.119 --> 00:05:20.160
But we all know that science is rarely simple.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.079
You might have multiple collaborators.

00:05:23.079 --> 00:05:25.799
Each might have their favorite computing language

00:05:25.799 --> 00:05:27.679
and a code editor.

00:05:27.679 --> 00:05:29.880
You might have multiple stages of a project,

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:32.640
each with their own level of feasibility

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:35.160
of what can be rerun with each edit

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:36.760
and what needs to be cached.

00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:40.000
So I can imagine something like a data analysis

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.359
where at the exploratory stage,

00:05:43.359 --> 00:05:47.119
it's totally fine to sort of run your code over and over

00:05:47.119 --> 00:05:50.519
as you're an iterate easily when you're exploring the data,

00:05:50.519 --> 00:05:53.959
making some simple visualizations for your own use.

00:05:53.959 --> 00:05:56.559
But when you get to a point where

00:05:56.559 --> 00:05:58.399
maybe you're building some models

00:05:58.399 --> 00:06:00.320
that take a little bit of time to run,

00:06:01.359 --> 00:06:03.559
your needs might change.

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:07.359
So something more complex could be one

00:06:07.359 --> 00:06:09.559
where you have a Quarto file,

00:06:09.559 --> 00:06:10.959
where you have your narrative

00:06:10.959 --> 00:06:13.559
and maybe some code cells in there as well.

00:06:13.559 --> 00:06:15.880
But you also have a bunch of R scripts

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:18.519
that lay around in your project.

00:06:18.519 --> 00:06:20.200
I tend to do this very often

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:23.720
where I'll have a sort of a manuscript project

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:26.600
where maybe I have something like a data folder

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:30.160
and inside of that, a raw data and a process data folder.

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:33.200
And I just use some simple R scripts to grab the data,

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:35.920
clean it up, reshape it and get it to the point

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:38.920
where I'm going to be doing modeling or analysis,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:43.480
write it out and then ingest it into my Quarto file.

00:06:43.480 --> 00:06:45.959
And then I might be outputting to something like a PDF

00:06:45.959 --> 00:06:47.640
or a Word document.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:49.440
Quarto works nicely for this,

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:54.040
but you as the individual need to sort of like make sure

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:57.720
that any changes you make in these R scripts,

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:02.160
especially if they have outputs that are then being used

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:03.279
in the subsequent stage,

00:07:03.279 --> 00:07:06.600
that you end up being the person who is taking care of

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:10.399
when computation is run and how often.

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:13.040
Even more complex could be one

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:15.119
where you have multiple Quarto files.

00:07:15.119 --> 00:07:17.760
Maybe these are sort of like notebooks that you're using

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:22.079
for some narrative and some sort of intermediary figures

00:07:22.079 --> 00:07:24.119
as well as some final figures.

00:07:24.119 --> 00:07:27.640
A bunch of R scripts that some of them maybe R

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:30.359
and some of them maybe Python.

00:07:30.359 --> 00:07:33.359
This might be an individual project

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:36.920
where if you're sort of fluent and comfortable

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.640
in the two languages and you choose to do certain types

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:43.359
of tasks in one and another type of task in another.

00:07:44.959 --> 00:07:49.279
Alternatively, if you have a team of folks working

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:52.920
on the project, some of them might be Python users

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:54.679
and some of them might be R users

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:57.720
and chances are they're going to want to stick

00:07:57.720 --> 00:07:59.359
with their own languages.

00:07:59.359 --> 00:08:02.399
And again, we're sort of like you're having to write

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:04.239
to a PDF or a Word file,

00:08:04.239 --> 00:08:07.160
something a little bit that requires a little bit

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:10.519
more finesse than just writing out to HTML.

00:08:10.519 --> 00:08:13.640
So as this layer of complexity goes up,

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:15.519
how can we leverage Quarto

00:08:15.519 --> 00:08:20.519
for creating fully reproducible scientific manuscripts?

00:08:20.799 --> 00:08:21.640
Throughout this talk,

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.760
I'm going to refer to a notion called notebook.

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:27.119
So what do I mean by a notebook?

00:08:27.119 --> 00:08:29.119
What I mean is that a notebook is a document

00:08:29.119 --> 00:08:31.640
that contains both code and narrative.

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:34.919
So this could be a Jupyter notebook.

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:36.960
It could also be a Quarto document.

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:41.239
And I often tend to refer to QMD files as Quarto documents.

00:08:41.239 --> 00:08:43.840
If you're a long time R Markdown user,

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:46.080
you may not necessarily have called

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:49.479
all of your R Markdown files notebooks,

00:08:49.479 --> 00:08:52.960
but let's go ahead and call them notebooks collectively,

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:56.080
regardless of whether it's a Jupyter notebook

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:58.080
or a plain text Quarto document,

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:00.239
because ultimately these are both things

00:09:00.239 --> 00:09:05.239
that allow you to have sort of code and narrative

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:08.719
in the same document and execute the code in that document.

00:09:09.799 --> 00:09:12.320
So what is the current state of affairs?

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.760
Most computational science, honestly, is born in notebooks.

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:18.599
You start sort of fussing around with your data

00:09:18.599 --> 00:09:20.960
at the beginning of your analysis,

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:25.000
and then it builds into a bigger project.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.960
And it, well, either dies or ends in Word documents.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.359
That ends up being the culminating thing

00:09:31.359 --> 00:09:33.440
that you submit to a journal.

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:36.640
And for many projects, that's where things end.

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:40.559
That ends up being the published work.

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:45.080
And oftentimes, by the time the authors of that project

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:48.559
get to that point, they are done with it.

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:50.840
They probably don't want to see it

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:52.119
for a little bit of time.

00:09:52.119 --> 00:09:55.159
But you, as the person who might be reading that paper,

00:09:55.159 --> 00:09:57.880
that's exactly when your journey with that data starts.

00:09:57.880 --> 00:09:59.440
That's when you want to be able

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:01.599
to see the code, interact with it,

00:10:01.599 --> 00:10:03.359
maybe play around with the raw data.

00:10:03.359 --> 00:10:05.719
Maybe you find a project that's very similar

00:10:05.719 --> 00:10:07.440
to something you're working on,

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:10.479
and you are ready to get into the nitty gritty of it.

00:10:10.479 --> 00:10:13.880
But at that point, the folks who have originally worked

00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:17.119
on this manuscript have packaged things up

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:19.239
in a PDF or a Word document,

00:10:19.239 --> 00:10:22.000
and it doesn't tend to be interactive anymore.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:26.280
This notion of, I mean, the peer review

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:27.919
and publication workflow, in a way,

00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:30.840
do not support notebooks as research outputs.

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:34.960
They ask for the static Word or PDF documents.

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:39.039
Additionally, more complex scenarios

00:10:39.039 --> 00:10:41.239
involve a lot of manual finagling

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:44.239
to bring the project to a journal submission stage.

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:47.039
You might have a bunch of script files

00:10:47.039 --> 00:10:49.960
in a variety of languages, maybe a bunch of notebooks,

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:51.599
where you bring things together.

00:10:51.599 --> 00:10:54.640
But ultimately, if you don't have the style file

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:57.760
that goes along with that journal

00:10:57.760 --> 00:11:00.239
that you might be submitting to,

00:11:00.239 --> 00:11:03.080
you're probably going to be sort of breaking

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:05.239
the reproducibility cycle

00:11:05.239 --> 00:11:08.599
and maybe manually editing that document.

00:11:08.599 --> 00:11:12.440
So often during this process, reproducibility is lost,

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:16.320
or even if it's not lost, it can take a second seat

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:18.280
to the formatting requirements.

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:21.359
And ultimately, final submission

00:11:21.359 --> 00:11:25.080
rarely captures all computations,

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:28.359
which are at best relegated to supplementary materials.

00:11:28.359 --> 00:11:32.119
We may have all seen papers that might say,

00:11:33.119 --> 00:11:34.239
sort of in the appendix,

00:11:34.239 --> 00:11:36.200
say code is available in the appendix,

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:37.559
and then you go to the appendix,

00:11:37.559 --> 00:11:40.559
and it says code can be found in this GitHub repository.

00:11:43.119 --> 00:11:45.239
And then you go to the GitHub repository,

00:11:45.239 --> 00:11:47.119
and you can tell that this is just code

00:11:47.119 --> 00:11:49.119
that just got sort of like put in there

00:11:49.119 --> 00:11:53.640
at the very end of the authoring process,

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:56.840
not necessarily code that grew with the project.

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:58.919
And I should also mention that

00:11:58.919 --> 00:12:00.400
probably your final submission

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:02.679
doesn't need all of your computations.

00:12:02.679 --> 00:12:04.479
It's not meant to be a diary

00:12:04.479 --> 00:12:06.919
of everything that you've done along the way.

00:12:06.919 --> 00:12:08.719
It really is meant to capture

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:11.799
sort of the highlights of the research process,

00:12:11.799 --> 00:12:13.280
but it would be really nice

00:12:13.280 --> 00:12:15.719
to be able to sort of capture everything

00:12:16.719 --> 00:12:19.080
that happened along the way.

00:12:20.039 --> 00:12:22.400
And not just the selected figures and tables.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:25.760
So if what I'm saying resonates with you,

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:28.479
know that you are not alone in thinking

00:12:28.479 --> 00:12:32.239
that there is some work that we should be doing

00:12:32.239 --> 00:12:36.559
in terms of sort of bringing the publication process

00:12:36.559 --> 00:12:40.640
up to the high standards that we hold ourselves to

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:43.479
in terms of doing reproducible science.

00:12:43.479 --> 00:12:46.960
And what I mean by you're not alone is,

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:48.719
well, I certainly agree with you,

00:12:49.359 --> 00:12:52.239
the developers of Quarto certainly agree with you,

00:12:52.239 --> 00:12:54.440
but also there are many other folks,

00:12:54.440 --> 00:12:55.799
there are many other initiatives.

00:12:55.799 --> 00:12:58.559
One of them is called Notebooks Now.

00:12:58.559 --> 00:13:00.320
I've linked to their paper here

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:02.039
and I'll share the link to my slides

00:13:02.039 --> 00:13:04.080
at the very end as well.

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:05.599
If you're interested in the work

00:13:05.599 --> 00:13:10.320
that they have done over the last few years,

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:12.280
since 2019 or so,

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:14.039
and it basically brought together

00:13:14.039 --> 00:13:16.159
sort of folks from the development teams

00:13:16.159 --> 00:13:18.200
of Jupyter Notebooks and R Markdown

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:21.760
and also Quarto as well along the way.

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:26.760
And the idea was to sort of start creating

00:13:27.559 --> 00:13:32.039
these fully reproducible manuscripts

00:13:32.039 --> 00:13:34.719
that also embed the computation along with it.

00:13:34.719 --> 00:13:36.919
And what I'm going to be talking today

00:13:36.919 --> 00:13:41.719
is basically an effort sort of in that direction as well.

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:45.960
So roadmap to fully reproducible scientific manuscripts

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:47.559
that are not just PDFs,

00:13:47.559 --> 00:13:50.440
that are the outputs of a single QMD file,

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:54.239
and which I think this represents a lot of scientific work

00:13:54.239 --> 00:13:56.080
that's being published today.

00:13:56.080 --> 00:13:59.479
So we need an end-to-end scholarly publishing workflow

00:13:59.479 --> 00:14:01.640
that treats Jupyter and Quarto notebooks

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:05.159
as primary element of scientific record.

00:14:05.159 --> 00:14:06.760
Another piece of the puzzle is that

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:08.359
we need a publication process

00:14:08.359 --> 00:14:12.200
that elevates transparent and reproducible work by authors,

00:14:12.200 --> 00:14:15.159
where the data and software together with the narrative

00:14:15.159 --> 00:14:17.200
are documented, shared,

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:19.960
and also archived along with the paper.

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:23.799
So the paper that gets published is not just the single PDF,

00:14:23.799 --> 00:14:27.799
but an archive of all the compute that goes along with it.

00:14:27.799 --> 00:14:30.880
And ideally, it would be great if there was new forms

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:33.559
of credit to the wider research community,

00:14:33.559 --> 00:14:37.200
including the research software engineers or research,

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:39.760
yeah, including research software engineers.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:44.440
So what I'm, and that bit is probably more advocacy

00:14:44.479 --> 00:14:46.039
from folks who are involved

00:14:46.039 --> 00:14:49.159
with sort of journal publications,

00:14:49.159 --> 00:14:53.880
journal editors, or even faculty and researchers.

00:14:53.880 --> 00:14:57.640
And that's not necessarily what I'm talking about today

00:14:57.640 --> 00:14:59.159
is going to be addressing,

00:14:59.159 --> 00:15:02.320
but I do wanna note that as we bring in new tools

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:07.320
and technologies to the sort of the toolkit of researchers,

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:13.640
we are asking them to do maybe a little bit of extra work,

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:16.400
at least they're having to learn a new tool.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:19.000
And it would be great if there was sort of credit given

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:20.280
for this as well.

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:22.799
But what I'm going to talk mostly about today

00:15:22.799 --> 00:15:27.080
are addressing the first two pieces of the puzzle.

00:15:27.080 --> 00:15:30.960
So with Quarto, if you're familiar with Quarto,

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:33.880
you probably know already that Quarto can be authored

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:35.960
in your favorite code editor.

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:38.159
It can render from a QMD file,

00:15:38.159 --> 00:15:41.440
which is a plain text file or a Jupyter notebook,

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:44.880
to PDF, Word, HTML, what have you.

00:15:46.359 --> 00:15:50.280
You can execute code in R, Python, and more.

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:53.799
You can apply journal styles to your outputs

00:15:53.799 --> 00:15:55.280
with Quarto extensions.

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:59.479
I saw that one of the attendees shared in the chat

00:15:59.479 --> 00:16:03.719
linked to the Quarto journals repository.

00:16:04.559 --> 00:16:09.159
And you can publish to GitHub Pages, Netlify, and more.

00:16:09.159 --> 00:16:14.159
Now, you can also, with Quarto projects,

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:18.159
orchestrate multiple inputs and outputs.

00:16:18.159 --> 00:16:21.440
And I will say that with a new project type,

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:23.640
starting with Quarto 1.4,

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:26.320
which was released earlier this year,

00:16:27.599 --> 00:16:30.239
you can orchestrate multiple inputs and outputs

00:16:30.239 --> 00:16:32.479
with embedded computing

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:35.119
using this project type called manuscript.

00:16:35.119 --> 00:16:38.280
And that's what we're going to be looking at today.

00:16:38.280 --> 00:16:41.440
So a new project type, manuscript.

00:16:42.799 --> 00:16:45.520
In addition to doing everything you can with Quarto,

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:48.679
you can now produce manuscripts in multiple formats,

00:16:48.679 --> 00:16:51.599
so including LaTeX and MS Word formats

00:16:51.599 --> 00:16:53.799
that may be required by journals,

00:16:53.799 --> 00:16:56.039
and give your readers easy access

00:16:56.039 --> 00:16:58.719
to all of the formats through our website.

00:16:58.719 --> 00:17:00.799
And you can also publish computations

00:17:00.799 --> 00:17:04.239
from one or more notebooks alongside the manuscript,

00:17:04.239 --> 00:17:07.520
which allows your readers to basically dive into your code

00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:09.599
and view it or even interact with it

00:17:09.599 --> 00:17:12.040
in a virtual environment.

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:14.920
So let's go ahead and write a manuscript.

00:17:14.920 --> 00:17:19.920
One of the approaches is you can use the Quarto command,

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:25.199
Quarto create project manuscript,

00:17:25.199 --> 00:17:27.160
and then give the name of your manuscript,

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:31.040
and then easy peasy, just add your manuscript content,

00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:32.839
which is all of your science.

00:17:32.839 --> 00:17:36.239
Alternatively, in the Quarto documentation,

00:17:36.239 --> 00:17:38.920
you'll see that there's a sample repository

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:41.640
that you can clone and start with that.

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:44.760
So sometimes starting with sort of an empty project

00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:47.239
can be a bit more daunting than starting with something

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:50.280
that has some of the pieces that are already working.

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:53.000
So if you're interested in that, you can take that too.

00:17:54.119 --> 00:17:56.439
And I would strongly recommend

00:17:56.439 --> 00:17:59.000
that you track your project with Git

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.520
and host it on GitHub for easy publishing.

00:18:01.520 --> 00:18:04.439
And that's the workflow that I'm going to demo today.

00:18:07.239 --> 00:18:09.680
So we're going to take approach one,

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:12.800
which is creating a new project.

00:18:12.800 --> 00:18:17.479
And so I'm creating a project called Indo RCT.

00:18:20.119 --> 00:18:22.160
And in that project,

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:26.959
when I run Quarto create project manuscript Indo RCT,

00:18:26.959 --> 00:18:29.680
I can see that Quarto gives me some options.

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:34.640
It says that it created a underscore Quarto YAML file.

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:36.719
What that means is that's the file

00:18:36.719 --> 00:18:37.920
that has the metadata

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:39.959
for how your project should come together.

00:18:39.959 --> 00:18:42.920
We're going to look into the contents of that in a second.

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:46.439
It also created an index.qmd file.

00:18:46.439 --> 00:18:48.640
And that file is basically

00:18:48.640 --> 00:18:52.239
where the content of your manuscript goes.

00:18:52.239 --> 00:18:56.520
And it also comes with a references.bib file as well,

00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:59.280
acknowledging that you're writing a scientific manuscript.

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:01.160
Obviously, you're going to have a bibliography

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:02.959
that goes along with it.

00:19:02.959 --> 00:19:06.640
And then in an interactive menu,

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:09.640
it asks you, do you want to open it with VS Code?

00:19:09.640 --> 00:19:11.400
Or do you want to open it with RStudio?

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:13.239
Or do you not want to open it at all?

00:19:14.599 --> 00:19:17.800
You can use Quarto with really any text editor

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:19.560
and then run your Quarto commands

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:21.400
in the terminal alongside it.

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:26.400
But since most of us tend to use Quarto with an IDE,

00:19:26.719 --> 00:19:28.439
these are the two options given to you.

00:19:28.439 --> 00:19:30.719
So I'm going to choose RStudio.

00:19:30.719 --> 00:19:33.280
And here is what my project would look like

00:19:34.439 --> 00:19:36.400
at the beginning of my,

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:40.839
soon as I launch, sort of create this manuscript.

00:19:40.839 --> 00:19:42.880
I can see in my files tab

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:46.520
that I have that underscore Quarto.yaml file

00:19:46.520 --> 00:19:48.599
and my index.qmd file.

00:19:48.599 --> 00:19:52.119
And since I chose to open this in RStudio,

00:19:54.280 --> 00:19:58.680
I also get an Rproj file that goes along with it as well.

00:19:58.680 --> 00:20:00.680
I recommend having one of those files

00:20:01.439 --> 00:20:02.280
in each one of your projects.

00:20:02.280 --> 00:20:05.560
And if you sort of like launch a new project from RStudio,

00:20:05.560 --> 00:20:06.959
you'll get that for free.

00:20:06.959 --> 00:20:09.920
It allows you to sort of like control

00:20:09.920 --> 00:20:11.920
some of your authoring experience.

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:15.920
And I'll give a couple of examples of options

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:18.199
that are available to you in your Rproj file

00:20:18.199 --> 00:20:21.119
that might be helpful, especially for manuscripts.

00:20:21.119 --> 00:20:23.119
And finally, your references file.

00:20:23.119 --> 00:20:25.280
So let's take a look.

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:28.319
In that Quarto underscore Quarto.yaml file,

00:20:28.319 --> 00:20:31.439
this is sort of what you get as a bare bones.

00:20:31.439 --> 00:20:34.640
We have, we're saying that we're creating a project

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:36.800
and the type is manuscript,

00:20:36.800 --> 00:20:41.800
and our article is in a file called index.qmd to begin with.

00:20:42.040 --> 00:20:45.079
You can also see that I have multiple formats

00:20:45.079 --> 00:20:48.040
that I'm creating, HTML, Docx,

00:20:48.040 --> 00:20:50.640
so a Word document, and a Jax.

00:20:50.640 --> 00:20:53.439
So that's a bundle of all of your documents

00:20:53.439 --> 00:20:56.959
that some of the journals accept,

00:20:56.959 --> 00:20:59.599
or at least the sort of the notebooks now.

00:20:59.599 --> 00:21:03.000
Folks have been sort of trying to move journals

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:07.400
towards sort of grabbing this archive

00:21:07.400 --> 00:21:12.119
that goes along with your manuscript

00:21:12.119 --> 00:21:16.760
to sort of have a full archive of all of the work

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:18.439
that has gone into that project.

00:21:18.439 --> 00:21:20.239
And we can do other formats as well.

00:21:20.239 --> 00:21:23.160
And we're gonna reveal the PDF format in a little bit

00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:26.400
when we open up our sample project.

00:21:26.959 --> 00:21:29.280
And here's what our finished document looks like.

00:21:29.280 --> 00:21:33.280
So let me go ahead and make my script a little bit bigger.

00:21:33.280 --> 00:21:35.400
And I wanna thank Peter Higgins

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:38.760
who shared some sample code with me

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:42.520
and sort of pointed me to this paper

00:21:42.520 --> 00:21:44.359
for which there is some,

00:21:44.359 --> 00:21:47.319
there's a R package with the data available.

00:21:47.319 --> 00:21:50.640
So I've gone ahead and recreated the paper,

00:21:50.640 --> 00:21:53.000
not all of it, but majority of it.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.040
So let's go ahead and sort of go forward.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:22:00.000
And I've also given a, as you can see a disclaimer here

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:01.880
saying this is not original work.

00:22:01.880 --> 00:22:04.319
This is just a reproduction of this paper

00:22:04.319 --> 00:22:08.319
for the purposes of demoing quarto manuscripts.

00:22:08.319 --> 00:22:13.319
So in this published paper

00:22:13.599 --> 00:22:17.920
that's currently published this version on GitHub pages,

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:21.599
you can see that I have some metadata up here.

00:22:21.599 --> 00:22:24.160
We'll get to the other formats in a second.

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:26.880
And as I scroll down my abstract,

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:28.959
I also have some links that would take me

00:22:28.959 --> 00:22:31.560
to the GitHub repository for this,

00:22:31.560 --> 00:22:33.880
as well as a binder link.

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:35.680
We'll get to that in a second.

00:22:35.680 --> 00:22:39.880
And then I have a table of contents that I get by default,

00:22:39.880 --> 00:22:42.000
as well as some embedded notebooks

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.599
that we're going to talk about in a second as well.

00:22:44.599 --> 00:22:46.439
But I'm gonna sort of scroll down

00:22:46.439 --> 00:22:49.599
to see like what a quarto manuscript looks like

00:22:51.319 --> 00:22:54.079
sort of at a high level

00:22:54.880 --> 00:22:56.359
when published as an HTML document.

00:22:56.359 --> 00:22:58.640
Some of the neat things you get are

00:22:58.640 --> 00:23:01.959
each of your references are hoverable.

00:23:01.959 --> 00:23:05.119
So you can actually sort of like hover over them.

00:23:05.119 --> 00:23:09.640
And then when we get to something like figures,

00:23:09.640 --> 00:23:11.880
let's scroll down a little bit more.

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:18.599
And here, for example, we have a reference to our figure one.

00:23:18.599 --> 00:23:21.280
You can see, I can similarly hover over that

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:23.800
and get a sneak preview of my figure

00:23:24.479 --> 00:23:26.680
or I can scroll down and see my figure

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:29.560
that has been created with some R code.

00:23:29.560 --> 00:23:33.520
And you can also see that the code for this figure

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:35.719
actually lives in another notebook

00:23:35.719 --> 00:23:38.560
that has been embedded with my manuscript.

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:41.079
So we'll demo that in a second as well.

00:23:41.079 --> 00:23:44.560
You'll be able to see here that I have some numbers

00:23:46.400 --> 00:23:48.599
that are sort of in my text.

00:23:48.599 --> 00:23:50.119
We'll take a look at the source code

00:23:50.119 --> 00:23:52.160
for this manuscript in a second,

00:23:52.160 --> 00:23:55.199
but leveraging standard Quarto functionality

00:23:55.199 --> 00:24:00.160
of inline code, here, these numbers

00:24:00.160 --> 00:24:02.439
are actually not hard-coded,

00:24:02.439 --> 00:24:05.079
but generated with inline code.

00:24:05.079 --> 00:24:09.479
You'll also see that as I sort of like highlight some text,

00:24:09.479 --> 00:24:14.479
I'm getting this option to either actually do a highlight,

00:24:15.119 --> 00:24:18.000
let me not log in right now, or annotate.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.719
So I have enabled hypothesis,

00:24:22.280 --> 00:24:26.560
which is sort of an online annotation tool for this project.

00:24:26.560 --> 00:24:30.479
It takes just one line of code in your YAML file

00:24:30.479 --> 00:24:32.520
that we're going to see in a second.

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:35.359
And it allows you to sort of add annotations,

00:24:35.359 --> 00:24:38.479
which might be helpful for collaboration.

00:24:38.479 --> 00:24:41.079
I see that there's one question in the chat,

00:24:41.079 --> 00:24:43.599
and I feel like this is a good moment to address that.

00:24:43.599 --> 00:24:45.880
We can go from Quarto to Word,

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:48.760
but can we go back from Word to Quarto?

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:52.160
No, there isn't a straightforward way.

00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:54.719
That is a Quarto, native Quarto tool

00:24:54.719 --> 00:24:57.160
for going back from Word to Quarto.

00:24:57.160 --> 00:25:02.160
So if you use Word for track changes and review of work,

00:25:03.839 --> 00:25:07.079
you don't have a way of sort of slurping those back

00:25:07.079 --> 00:25:09.920
into your index.qmd file.

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:14.920
However, if you sort of host your manuscript

00:25:15.760 --> 00:25:17.079
during the development stage

00:25:17.079 --> 00:25:19.040
on something like GitHub Pages,

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:22.400
your collaborators could also leave comments

00:25:22.400 --> 00:25:24.040
using this tool as well.

00:25:24.040 --> 00:25:28.599
So this may be one way of potentially sort of veering away

00:25:28.599 --> 00:25:30.680
from comments in a Word document,

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:33.599
which might be particularly helpful for collaborators

00:25:33.599 --> 00:25:35.280
who may not be the ones who want to dive

00:25:35.280 --> 00:25:38.239
into the GitHub repository and write the code.

00:25:38.239 --> 00:25:40.239
All right, so I'm going to scroll down to see,

00:25:40.239 --> 00:25:42.800
we have some figures, we have some tables,

00:25:42.800 --> 00:25:44.599
so on and so forth.

00:25:44.599 --> 00:25:48.079
And at the end, we have a list of references as well.

