And then I have a somewhat lengthy abstract

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:20.000
that goes along with this paper as well.

00:29:21.199 --> 00:29:24.599
In the PDF document, from all of this front matter,

00:29:24.599 --> 00:29:27.839
we only sort of expose the relevant

00:29:27.839 --> 00:29:29.560
and the required metadata

00:29:29.560 --> 00:29:31.599
that's required by the journal.

00:29:31.599 --> 00:29:34.760
And similarly for the Word document as well,

00:29:34.760 --> 00:29:39.359
it's only the relevant and required metadata get exposed.

00:29:39.359 --> 00:29:43.680
So you don't have to change the document YAML

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:47.439
as you are changing perhaps the venue

00:29:47.439 --> 00:29:49.160
of your paper, for example.

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:53.319
I also mentioned embedded computation.

00:29:53.319 --> 00:29:54.800
So let's take a look at that.

00:29:54.800 --> 00:29:56.199
So what do we mean by that?

00:29:56.199 --> 00:29:59.959
I'm going to go down to one of my figures.

00:30:03.280 --> 00:30:05.359
Let's go ahead.

00:30:05.359 --> 00:30:06.199
And here we go.

00:30:06.199 --> 00:30:08.719
So this is one of our figures.

00:30:08.719 --> 00:30:13.719
It has a caption and it also underneath the caption says,

00:30:13.959 --> 00:30:18.520
there's a link to a source notebook that says,

00:30:18.520 --> 00:30:21.199
this is the notebook called Enrollments and Outcomes.

00:30:21.199 --> 00:30:24.439
You can see that the same notebook is also linked

00:30:24.439 --> 00:30:25.920
sort of on the side as well.

00:30:26.599 --> 00:30:29.640
So you can customize whether you want the linking

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:31.319
only under the figure,

00:30:31.319 --> 00:30:34.479
only sort of at the document level or none

00:30:34.479 --> 00:30:36.239
if you don't want to do that.

00:30:36.239 --> 00:30:38.640
And if we go ahead and click on this,

00:30:38.640 --> 00:30:41.680
I actually get to see the notebook

00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:44.319
where this computation was done.

00:30:44.319 --> 00:30:47.520
And I can have a little bit more narrative here

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:49.239
in a more realistic setting,

00:30:49.239 --> 00:30:54.239
maybe even other computation that is not part of the,

00:30:54.439 --> 00:30:59.439
that is not necessarily part of the final paper.

00:30:59.880 --> 00:31:02.800
And ultimately the figure is produced here

00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:06.040
and simply embedded with an embed shortcode

00:31:06.040 --> 00:31:09.319
into my Quarto document.

00:31:14.199 --> 00:31:15.040
All right.

00:31:15.040 --> 00:31:18.280
So let's go ahead and take a tour

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:21.839
of how to author one of these documents with RStudio.

00:31:22.839 --> 00:31:27.839
I am going to open this document on my, in RStudio.

00:31:29.119 --> 00:31:33.119
And my goal is not to give sort of a full account

00:31:33.119 --> 00:31:38.119
of doing everything about Quarto in RStudio,

00:31:38.119 --> 00:31:41.359
but there may be a few handy tools that you're used to

00:31:41.359 --> 00:31:44.880
that might be nice to see that they work for a manuscript

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:46.560
or there may be some handy tools

00:31:46.560 --> 00:31:49.439
that you haven't necessarily explored in Quarto.

00:31:50.400 --> 00:31:53.599
Let's start with the embedding computations one

00:31:53.599 --> 00:31:56.719
since that's sort of the new kid in town.

00:31:56.719 --> 00:32:01.400
So I'm going to go down to where I had my results here.

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:05.359
So let's take a look.

00:32:05.359 --> 00:32:09.000
This is one of the other figures that we have embedded.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:13.199
So you can see that I am using an embed shortcode.

00:32:13.199 --> 00:32:14.760
And in this embed shortcode,

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:18.319
I'm pointing to a folder called notebooks.

00:32:18.319 --> 00:32:21.079
So we can see that here in my files pane.

00:32:21.079 --> 00:32:22.680
And then inside of it,

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:27.680
I'm pointing to a QMD file called incidences.qmd.

00:32:27.719 --> 00:32:31.680
In this particular example, I've kept only to R code

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:34.239
since this was an R medicine talk,

00:32:34.239 --> 00:32:37.640
but you can have IPython notebooks here as well.

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:42.280
And either in QMD documents or IPython notebook documents,

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:45.560
you can have either R or Python code.

00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:47.280
And that's sort of the neat thing of it

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:49.800
while in a single QMD document,

00:32:49.800 --> 00:32:52.119
you don't get to have multiple languages

00:32:52.119 --> 00:32:54.640
without the use of something like reticulate

00:32:54.640 --> 00:32:59.079
in separate QMD documents, this is possible to do.

00:32:59.079 --> 00:33:02.400
And so you can imagine your figure one being generated,

00:33:02.400 --> 00:33:04.959
say with Python and an IPython notebook,

00:33:04.959 --> 00:33:09.079
your figure two being generated with R in a QMD,

00:33:09.079 --> 00:33:11.319
and then you can embed each one of them

00:33:11.319 --> 00:33:14.000
in a single index.qmd file.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:19.000
So if we go ahead and dive into this incidences.qmd file,

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:24.160
you can see that this is where I'm doing the heavy lifting

00:33:24.160 --> 00:33:25.800
of the data analysis.

00:33:25.800 --> 00:33:28.079
So I'm loading my packages,

00:33:28.079 --> 00:33:33.000
I am writing my code for creating these plots.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.439
We can go ahead and sort of show

00:33:35.439 --> 00:33:37.040
what these plots look like.

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:43.040
And when I do, I also give a label to my code chunk.

00:33:47.359 --> 00:33:52.280
And that label must start with FIG, so fig dash.

00:33:52.280 --> 00:33:54.599
If I want to do cross-referencing

00:33:54.599 --> 00:33:58.439
and automatic counting of my figures in the quarto document,

00:33:58.439 --> 00:34:01.359
and then I can name it whatever I want after that.

00:34:01.359 --> 00:34:04.439
And I also need to give it a caption as well.

00:34:04.439 --> 00:34:05.680
And I'm going to,

00:34:07.359 --> 00:34:12.360
the code cell option for captions is fig dash cat.

00:34:13.199 --> 00:34:16.800
So if we just take a note of this label,

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:19.879
fig dash incidences adverse events,

00:34:19.879 --> 00:34:23.080
and go back to our index.qmd file,

00:34:23.080 --> 00:34:26.479
we'll be able to see that that's how we refer

00:34:26.479 --> 00:34:29.840
to that particular code chunk and say,

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:31.560
include that figure for me

00:34:31.560 --> 00:34:33.439
and nothing else from that document.

00:34:33.439 --> 00:34:38.439
And that linking is what allows us to sort of link

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:43.320
to that source document in our published manuscript.

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:46.800
You can also see though that not everything has to happen

00:34:46.800 --> 00:34:48.800
in a separate notebook.

00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:52.120
So oftentimes for me, I might have some figures

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:55.800
that are perhaps more computationally intensive to produce

00:34:55.800 --> 00:34:59.280
because maybe they're plotting some modeling results

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:00.439
or something like that.

00:35:00.439 --> 00:35:02.000
But I might also have some stuff

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
that's like pretty cheap to calculate

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.959
that I don't need to create a whole other notebook for.

00:35:06.959 --> 00:35:09.879
For example, in this case, I have one table,

00:35:09.879 --> 00:35:12.879
sort of like a table one sort of thing.

00:35:12.879 --> 00:35:16.600
Let's go ahead and generate that table.

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:21.600
So something like this, like a exploratory table

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:25.199
that gives you at a glance, some information about your data

00:35:25.199 --> 00:35:29.360
that table is just created in my index.qmd file,

00:35:29.360 --> 00:35:30.800
not in a separate notebook.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:34.439
So I can sort of mix and match based on my needs,

00:35:34.439 --> 00:35:38.639
how I want certain figures and tables to be generated.

00:35:38.639 --> 00:35:42.040
And additionally, as you can see in this document,

00:35:42.040 --> 00:35:47.040
I have some inline R code that I am able to run

00:35:48.479 --> 00:35:53.479
and I have code chunks where I calculate these numbers

00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:56.399
like percentage with a particular incidence

00:35:56.399 --> 00:35:58.639
or number of patients in the placebo

00:35:58.639 --> 00:36:00.560
and the treatment group.

00:36:01.320 --> 00:36:02.159
So on and so forth.

00:36:02.159 --> 00:36:05.439
And then I'm pulling those numbers in using inline code.

00:36:06.679 --> 00:36:10.479
So that's sort of how the computational embedding works.

00:36:10.479 --> 00:36:12.560
Another neat thing is,

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:15.439
so let's go ahead and render this again,

00:36:15.439 --> 00:36:17.040
the cross-referencing.

00:36:17.040 --> 00:36:20.760
So with Corto, you have a few options for cross-referencing

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:24.959
for how you actually want the cross-references to happen.

00:36:24.959 --> 00:36:26.600
But something that is constant

00:36:26.600 --> 00:36:30.639
is that if you are cross-referencing a figure,

00:36:30.639 --> 00:36:33.639
they must start with fig dash.

00:36:33.639 --> 00:36:36.439
And if you are cross-referencing a table,

00:36:36.439 --> 00:36:37.399
they must start with,

00:36:37.399 --> 00:36:40.520
the labels must start with table dash.

00:36:40.520 --> 00:36:43.679
So if I wanted to make another cross-reference

00:36:43.679 --> 00:36:47.479
to this figure, say at the end of my paragraph,

00:36:47.479 --> 00:36:48.360
for some reason,

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:50.879
one of the things I can do in the visual editor

00:36:50.879 --> 00:36:55.879
in RStudio is bring up my insert anything tool

00:36:56.239 --> 00:37:01.080
so that is command forward shift and say cross-reference.

00:37:02.439 --> 00:37:05.199
And then I can choose from the figures

00:37:05.199 --> 00:37:06.479
that are available to me

00:37:06.479 --> 00:37:09.360
or from the tables that are available to me.

00:37:10.239 --> 00:37:12.560
Let's go ahead and do this.

00:37:12.560 --> 00:37:15.280
And then I can render the document, for example,

00:37:15.280 --> 00:37:19.040
and we'll be able to see a cross-reference to that.

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:23.840
If these are figures that are in the embedded notebooks,

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:27.719
they're not going to show up in your selection editor.

00:37:27.719 --> 00:37:30.399
So for something like this,

00:37:30.399 --> 00:37:32.679
I would need to actually take a note

00:37:32.679 --> 00:37:36.399
of the code chunk label

00:37:36.399 --> 00:37:40.120
from the notebook that I am embedding.

00:37:40.120 --> 00:37:44.800
And one more thing I wanted to demo was citation.

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:49.800
So let's go ahead and take a look at,

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:55.840
let's imagine that I actually wanted to cite this paper,

00:37:55.840 --> 00:37:59.360
which is the actual paper that I am reconstructing here.

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:01.520
So I have the DOI of this paper.

00:38:01.520 --> 00:38:04.040
I'm going to go ahead and copy that.

00:38:04.040 --> 00:38:08.679
And let's say that I actually want to cite that paper

00:38:08.679 --> 00:38:11.439
right in this call out box as well.

00:38:11.439 --> 00:38:12.639
I'm going to once again,

00:38:12.639 --> 00:38:14.840
well, I can use my insert anything tool again,

00:38:14.840 --> 00:38:16.679
command forward slash,

00:38:16.719 --> 00:38:20.360
or I could go to my insert menu

00:38:20.360 --> 00:38:23.840
and say, I want to insert a cross-reference.

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:27.719
Oh, I'm sorry, not a cross-reference.

00:38:27.719 --> 00:38:32.719
Say I want to insert a citation and let's go to from DOI,

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:36.280
and I can go ahead and paste that DOI.

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:41.280
And here our studio is basically querying an API

00:38:41.879 --> 00:38:46.879
in order to sort of look for this paper with this DOI.

00:38:48.080 --> 00:38:50.040
And then I can go ahead,

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:54.919
it creates a sort of a label for this reference for me.

00:38:54.919 --> 00:38:57.520
I can choose if I want that to be an in-text,

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:01.199
so without the parentheses or not in-text citation,

00:39:01.199 --> 00:39:03.679
and I can go ahead and say, insert.

00:39:03.679 --> 00:39:08.199
So what happened is I was able to sort of create

00:39:08.199 --> 00:39:11.639
this bib entry without having to do the copy pasting

00:39:11.639 --> 00:39:14.760
from Google Scholar that I tend to do.

00:39:14.760 --> 00:39:19.760
And if we go ahead and open up our references.bib file,

00:39:23.479 --> 00:39:28.280
and look for this tag,

00:39:28.280 --> 00:39:30.919
you'll be able to see that that was inserted

00:39:30.919 --> 00:39:33.199
to the end of our references file.

00:39:33.199 --> 00:39:35.879
So that just got inserted now.

00:39:35.879 --> 00:39:38.679
And let's go ahead and render this document.

00:39:47.919 --> 00:39:51.239
And our citation has basically been added here.

00:39:52.760 --> 00:39:57.280
Let's go ahead and open up that citation tool one more time.

00:39:57.280 --> 00:39:58.600
You'll be able to see that

00:39:58.600 --> 00:40:01.239
if you already have an existing bib file,

00:40:01.239 --> 00:40:03.560
you can easily select from it

00:40:03.560 --> 00:40:06.760
and it displays the titles of the papers,

00:40:06.760 --> 00:40:09.239
which makes it really easy to use.

00:40:09.239 --> 00:40:13.159
You can use a link as Zotero library,

00:40:13.159 --> 00:40:15.360
if so, if you commonly use that.

00:40:15.360 --> 00:40:17.719
And in addition to from DOI,

00:40:17.719 --> 00:40:21.760
you can link from Crossref, Datasite, PubMed,

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:25.399
or if you're looking for a citation for an R package,

00:40:25.399 --> 00:40:28.719
you can go ahead and look for that here

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:33.360
and insert that citation as well.

00:40:34.560 --> 00:40:35.399
All right.

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:43.439
So what's next from here?

00:40:43.439 --> 00:40:47.560
Well, we can actually dive into the code as well.

00:40:47.560 --> 00:40:48.840
So what do I mean by that?

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:51.080
You've seen that you can peruse the code

00:40:51.080 --> 00:40:54.840
underlying the figures and tables in the manuscript,

00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:58.040
but what if you wanted to actually interact with the code

00:40:58.040 --> 00:41:01.439
in a computational environment that's just a click away

00:41:01.439 --> 00:41:04.199
and that has all the software and packages needed

00:41:04.199 --> 00:41:06.120
to reproduce the manuscript?

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:12.320
Back in 2019, Nature actually published a paper

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:17.600
that basically, or an article that said,

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:21.560
there's a paper that was published in eLife

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:24.600
that lets scientists play with each other's results.

00:41:24.600 --> 00:41:27.080
So this basically had these,

00:41:27.080 --> 00:41:29.679
the paper had these figures.

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:30.719
If you clicked on them,

00:41:30.719 --> 00:41:32.959
it took you to a computational environment

00:41:32.959 --> 00:41:34.879
and you can basically see the code

00:41:34.879 --> 00:41:37.000
and play around with things and said things like,

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:38.399
what if I change my threshold?

00:41:38.399 --> 00:41:41.199
How would my results change or something like that?

00:41:42.800 --> 00:41:46.040
As of today, those links are dead, unfortunately.

00:41:46.040 --> 00:41:49.520
So it has been some time, since 2019,

00:41:49.520 --> 00:41:53.719
but at the same time, we want to make sure that,

00:41:53.719 --> 00:41:56.879
if we are saying that we have embedded computing,

00:41:56.879 --> 00:41:58.800
that it actually stays embedded

00:41:58.800 --> 00:42:02.479
because in a way, it's been a while since 2019,

00:42:02.479 --> 00:42:06.560
but in a way, you should not expect scientific results

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:09.520
to go away in five years and not be accessible

00:42:09.520 --> 00:42:12.520
in the original format that they were published.

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:15.360
So with Corto, one of your options

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:18.479
is to use the service called Binder.

00:42:18.479 --> 00:42:21.320
So you can simply say in your terminal,

00:42:21.320 --> 00:42:25.159
Corto use Binder in the project where your manuscript is.

00:42:26.159 --> 00:42:29.719
And remember, I mentioned that we can go

00:42:29.719 --> 00:42:34.520
to the GitHub repository for our manuscript,

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:37.360
but we can also launch a Binder instance.

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:39.639
So let's go ahead and click on that.

00:42:39.639 --> 00:42:44.639
And it will take a second for this to launch.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:49.600
I have a version of this that I have already launched.

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:52.840
So I'm going to go ahead and share that with you

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:55.879
because as I said, it does take a little bit of time

00:42:55.879 --> 00:43:00.479
for the virtual environment to be built.

00:43:00.479 --> 00:43:03.879
But once it's done building, this is where it lands you.

00:43:04.840 --> 00:43:07.959
And then you can actually say,

00:43:07.959 --> 00:43:11.560
suppose you want to actually do your editing in RStudio,

00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:15.040
it will bring you to a window like this.

00:43:15.040 --> 00:43:18.879
There's a little bit of messages that are happening here,

00:43:18.879 --> 00:43:22.159
but this is not my local copy of this project.

00:43:22.520 --> 00:43:26.239
You can see that this actually is a version

00:43:26.239 --> 00:43:30.399
of this document that is on my Binder

00:43:30.399 --> 00:43:35.399
and all of my computations, my notebooks that I have used

00:43:35.879 --> 00:43:39.760
as part of my manuscript, as well as the manuscript itself

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:41.760
are available to me here.

00:43:46.719 --> 00:43:49.120
All right, so I had screenshots of those

00:43:49.120 --> 00:43:51.679
just in case the service went down.

00:43:51.679 --> 00:43:53.719
Live demos are always a little bit tricky,

00:43:53.719 --> 00:43:55.520
but we've been able to see that.

00:43:55.520 --> 00:43:57.040
All of the files are available.

00:43:57.040 --> 00:44:00.080
You can launch an instance in your favorite editor

00:44:00.080 --> 00:44:03.080
and then get to editing it.

00:44:03.080 --> 00:44:06.159
So if you would like to get started working

00:44:06.159 --> 00:44:11.159
with Corto Manuscripts, corto.org.docs.manuscripts

00:44:11.520 --> 00:44:15.280
is where I would recommend you find and get started again.

00:44:15.280 --> 00:44:17.959
It will walk you through a step-by-step tutorial

00:44:17.959 --> 00:44:19.959
with a sample repository.

