All right, so let me go ahead

00:46:03.600 --> 00:46:08.600
and I'll go ahead and start answering a few questions

00:46:09.399 --> 00:46:10.840
from the chat.

00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:12.439
One of the questions said,

00:46:12.439 --> 00:46:15.080
is embed the same as a source function

00:46:15.080 --> 00:46:18.639
that will execute an external QMD file?

00:46:18.639 --> 00:46:20.479
So very good question.

00:46:20.479 --> 00:46:23.360
Not 100% the same.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.080
So what the source function would do

00:46:28.080 --> 00:46:29.760
is it would like source it,

00:46:29.760 --> 00:46:33.120
which means that the computation would have to be run again.

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:35.959
That is not a requirement in this case.

00:46:35.959 --> 00:46:39.520
Something I haven't said much about in this presentation,

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:42.040
but I can touch on briefly here

00:46:42.120 --> 00:46:46.159
is that if we take a look at our Corto YAML,

00:46:46.159 --> 00:46:48.159
you can see that I'm also using

00:46:48.159 --> 00:46:50.959
the freeze functionality from Corto,

00:46:50.959 --> 00:46:52.679
which basically means that

00:46:52.679 --> 00:46:57.399
unless I have explicitly touched a QMD file,

00:46:57.399 --> 00:47:00.280
do not rerun the code in it.

00:47:00.280 --> 00:47:02.040
I can set freeze to false,

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:04.760
which would mean always rerun the code,

00:47:04.760 --> 00:47:06.439
or I can set freeze to true,

00:47:06.439 --> 00:47:11.000
which means never rerun the code unless I explicitly run it.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.919
My preference is usually to keep it at auto

00:47:13.919 --> 00:47:16.399
so that I don't have to be the one remembering,

00:47:16.399 --> 00:47:17.639
oh, I touched this file,

00:47:17.639 --> 00:47:20.479
I should rerun my computations again.

00:47:20.479 --> 00:47:22.639
But what this does is it sort of captures

00:47:22.639 --> 00:47:25.439
the computational results at the time

00:47:25.439 --> 00:47:28.639
and stores them in a freeze file.

00:47:28.639 --> 00:47:33.439
And basically the figures that are embedded

00:47:33.439 --> 00:47:35.560
are actually pulled from these.

00:47:35.560 --> 00:47:38.280
But the neat thing is that it's also not the same

00:47:38.280 --> 00:47:40.199
as include graphics either, right?

00:47:40.199 --> 00:47:42.560
So we're not just including the output,

00:47:42.560 --> 00:47:46.919
we're keeping that link to the code cell

00:47:46.919 --> 00:47:51.000
where the figure was actually created for your readers

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:53.840
or yourself to be able to track your work back

00:47:53.840 --> 00:47:56.360
without having to include all of that code

00:47:56.360 --> 00:47:58.320
in your manuscript document.

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:06.840
Another question, what about the data?

00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:08.639
Some data are clinical and protected,

00:48:08.639 --> 00:48:10.639
what are your thoughts on this?

00:48:10.639 --> 00:48:13.800
So this particular approach,

00:48:13.800 --> 00:48:16.040
creating manuscripts with Corto

00:48:16.040 --> 00:48:20.479
does not necessarily address the challenges

00:48:20.479 --> 00:48:22.800
around working with private data.

00:48:22.800 --> 00:48:24.719
It's not meant to necessarily address it.

00:48:24.719 --> 00:48:28.919
However, my guess is either all of this is happening

00:48:28.919 --> 00:48:31.560
in an environment where like you're using

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:36.560
all of the functionality of Corto manuscripts,

00:48:36.600 --> 00:48:40.639
but perhaps in your gitignore file,

00:48:40.639 --> 00:48:42.639
you are adding an ignore statement

00:48:42.639 --> 00:48:45.199
for not committing your data files

00:48:45.199 --> 00:48:47.080
to your GitHub repository.

00:48:47.080 --> 00:48:50.159
So in a way, the work that you share

00:48:50.159 --> 00:48:53.679
isn't 100% reproducible by somebody else,

00:48:53.679 --> 00:48:55.520
but enough of the code is there,

00:48:55.520 --> 00:48:59.719
the full sort of history of your code is there

00:48:59.719 --> 00:49:02.760
so that they are able to follow in your footsteps.

00:49:02.760 --> 00:49:06.520
And if you additionally include maybe some readme files

00:49:06.520 --> 00:49:08.520
that say our data was in this format,

00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:10.919
these were the headers or something like that,

00:49:10.919 --> 00:49:12.959
that might go a long way.

00:49:12.959 --> 00:49:15.360
Alternatively, you might be querying this data

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:17.800
from a protected environment

00:49:17.800 --> 00:49:19.719
so that it never actually makes it

00:49:19.719 --> 00:49:21.760
into a GitHub repository

00:49:21.760 --> 00:49:25.360
and others who don't have the right sort of privileges

00:49:25.360 --> 00:49:29.879
to access that data server never get to touch the data,

00:49:29.879 --> 00:49:32.600
but again, you get to use everything

00:49:33.479 --> 00:49:36.679
that Corto and Corto manuscripts offers otherwise.

00:49:39.199 --> 00:49:41.560
Another question in the Q&A tab is,

00:49:41.560 --> 00:49:44.159
what is the minimum version of R and Corto

00:49:44.159 --> 00:49:47.639
and R tools required to produce manuscripts?

00:49:47.639 --> 00:49:52.479
So the minimum version of Corto required is 1.4.

00:49:52.479 --> 00:49:56.159
Currently the release version is like 1.4.5

00:49:56.159 --> 00:49:57.000
or something like that.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.679
But if you download the release version of Corto

00:49:59.679 --> 00:50:01.639
from the Corto website,

00:50:01.679 --> 00:50:06.679
you'll be able to see that you can use Corto manuscripts.

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:10.760
The minimum R version,

00:50:11.719 --> 00:50:15.199
I don't know off the top of my head to be perfectly honest.

00:50:15.199 --> 00:50:17.280
However, something recent,

00:50:17.280 --> 00:50:20.280
but not necessarily the latest one is what I would say.

00:50:20.280 --> 00:50:25.280
In fact, I don't think that for many things,

00:50:25.520 --> 00:50:28.719
Corto does not require a particular R version.

00:50:28.719 --> 00:50:30.879
If you're working in RStudio,

00:50:30.879 --> 00:50:33.840
whatever the minimum version RStudio will work with,

00:50:33.840 --> 00:50:35.600
and it goes pretty far back,

00:50:35.600 --> 00:50:38.639
I believe should be good for manuscripts as well.

00:50:40.719 --> 00:50:43.840
So will the binder instance contain the same versions

00:50:43.840 --> 00:50:46.520
of R and packages, et cetera?

00:50:46.520 --> 00:50:48.239
The answer is yes, it will,

00:50:48.239 --> 00:50:53.239
because it is created with that Corto use binder function,

00:50:53.919 --> 00:50:56.399
which actually looks at the environment

00:50:56.399 --> 00:50:57.919
that you're working in.

00:50:57.959 --> 00:51:02.840
And you can see that when you, let's go here,

00:51:02.840 --> 00:51:06.959
when you actually run that command,

00:51:06.959 --> 00:51:11.959
it creates a few files for you that you are asked to,

00:51:12.719 --> 00:51:13.560
here we go,

00:51:13.560 --> 00:51:17.080
that you're asked to commit and push to your repository.

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:18.639
You can see, for example,

00:51:18.639 --> 00:51:22.600
which version of Corto being used, so on and so forth.

00:51:22.600 --> 00:51:27.600
And these are the instructions that my binder then uses

00:51:27.879 --> 00:51:29.639
in order to be able to,

00:51:30.879 --> 00:51:32.840
I think this was another one of those as well.

00:51:32.840 --> 00:51:34.399
So you can see the R version there

00:51:34.399 --> 00:51:37.639
in order to be able to sort of build

00:51:37.639 --> 00:51:39.399
that virtual environment.

00:51:42.879 --> 00:51:43.719
Let's see.

00:51:44.959 --> 00:51:46.679
So another question says,

00:51:46.679 --> 00:51:50.879
my manuscripts often involve more than 10 authors,

00:51:50.879 --> 00:51:53.280
each of which will edit the manuscript.

00:51:53.280 --> 00:51:57.280
Any way to incorporate revisions in such a workflow?

00:51:58.239 --> 00:52:00.199
Well, if all 10 of these authors

00:52:00.199 --> 00:52:02.879
are familiar with version control,

00:52:02.879 --> 00:52:05.360
I think this is a solved problem.

00:52:05.360 --> 00:52:08.760
They can all have a fork of the repository

00:52:08.760 --> 00:52:10.800
you're working in, make pull requests

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:12.879
or push domain directly,

00:52:12.879 --> 00:52:14.760
but be careful about what they're doing.

00:52:14.760 --> 00:52:17.280
And that's sort of done.

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:21.000
If some of the folks do not want to be

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:24.479
sort of cloning a data,

00:52:24.639 --> 00:52:27.199
cloning a GitHub repository

00:52:27.199 --> 00:52:31.320
and editing directly in a Corto document,

00:52:31.320 --> 00:52:36.320
in that case, I guess you or the folks in that group

00:52:36.639 --> 00:52:39.919
who are a little bit more sort of savvy

00:52:39.919 --> 00:52:44.760
around writing, around authoring computational notebooks,

00:52:44.760 --> 00:52:49.760
perhaps can provide some ways for them to provide feedback.

00:52:49.959 --> 00:52:52.280
It could be using hypothesis, as I said,

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:54.760
or it could be using just the word output,

00:52:54.760 --> 00:52:56.760
but ultimately you'll have to manually

00:52:56.760 --> 00:52:59.639
sort of incorporate their edits into this.

00:52:59.639 --> 00:53:03.199
I will say that I'm very sympathetic

00:53:03.199 --> 00:53:07.040
to scientists not necessarily wanting to learn

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:10.199
all of a sudden a whole new language as well

00:53:10.199 --> 00:53:12.159
in order to be able to doing edits.

00:53:12.159 --> 00:53:16.120
But if you're able to get your collaborators

00:53:16.120 --> 00:53:17.399
to the point where,

00:53:17.399 --> 00:53:20.080
if they're not going to be the ones writing the code,

00:53:20.080 --> 00:53:23.520
to the point where they might have RStudio installed,

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:28.520
perhaps, just that, or maybe a server version of that,

00:53:30.879 --> 00:53:33.840
linked to the Git repository

00:53:33.840 --> 00:53:36.919
where they can simply at least pull the changes,

00:53:36.919 --> 00:53:39.719
the latest changes, and then make edits,

00:53:39.719 --> 00:53:42.040
especially if all they're editing is the text.

00:53:42.040 --> 00:53:44.919
I think the visual editor is a great way

00:53:44.919 --> 00:53:48.000
of being able to do that without having to learn

00:53:48.040 --> 00:53:52.159
a whole new computational language

00:53:52.159 --> 00:53:54.399
and commit and push their results.

00:53:54.399 --> 00:53:56.719
That might be sort of meeting you halfway

00:53:56.719 --> 00:54:01.600
in a way where you get some mileage

00:54:01.600 --> 00:54:03.719
out of using this tooling

00:54:03.719 --> 00:54:05.639
and they also learn a little bit

00:54:05.639 --> 00:54:07.320
of something new along the way.

00:54:10.040 --> 00:54:15.040
All right, I think that might be answering

00:54:15.159 --> 00:54:17.639
the next question as well.

00:54:18.080 --> 00:54:21.879
It says that we can't copy the...

00:54:23.760 --> 00:54:27.239
I will take a look at how else I can share the links

00:54:27.239 --> 00:54:29.239
if copying is not possible.

00:54:31.159 --> 00:54:33.760
Binder is not a paid service.

00:54:34.959 --> 00:54:37.040
That being said, I think the fact

00:54:37.040 --> 00:54:40.239
that it's not a paid service might also mean

00:54:40.239 --> 00:54:43.679
that it's a little bit unclear

00:54:43.679 --> 00:54:45.639
how reliable it's going to be

00:54:45.639 --> 00:54:47.840
sort of further into the future.

00:54:47.840 --> 00:54:49.520
But other things you can use

00:54:49.520 --> 00:54:53.959
if you have a GitHub repository

00:54:53.959 --> 00:54:58.959
that goes with your core to a manuscript,

00:54:59.760 --> 00:55:02.399
you can also use dev containers as well.

00:55:02.399 --> 00:55:06.040
So that's another way of providing a virtual environment.

00:55:06.040 --> 00:55:07.560
And that's something you can simply do

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:10.040
using the GitHub UI as well.

00:55:12.399 --> 00:55:14.439
What about typist documents?

00:55:14.439 --> 00:55:19.439
So currently by default, this is using LaTeX

00:55:20.360 --> 00:55:25.239
but as sort of the typist ecosystem becomes more mature

00:55:25.239 --> 00:55:30.239
and the journal article sort of extensions

00:55:31.040 --> 00:55:34.280
also start to include typist solutions as well.

00:55:34.280 --> 00:55:36.959
Those will natively be sort of like available

00:55:36.959 --> 00:55:38.879
for Cordo manuscripts too.

00:55:38.879 --> 00:55:43.560
Right now, because I'm using a particular journal

00:55:44.840 --> 00:55:48.040
style for generating my PDF,

00:55:48.040 --> 00:55:51.679
and that style is provided with some LaTeX style

00:55:51.679 --> 00:55:54.479
like textile sheets, I'm going through LaTeX,

00:55:54.479 --> 00:55:59.439
but sort of any sort of development on the typist front

00:55:59.439 --> 00:56:03.280
should be able to be sort of used by Cordo manuscripts

00:56:03.280 --> 00:56:08.280
as soon as the extensions become available

00:56:09.120 --> 00:56:12.280
for generating those documents with the journal style.

00:56:15.439 --> 00:56:17.320
All right, let's see.

00:56:23.560 --> 00:56:26.800
Another question is, if I have a medical writer,

00:56:26.800 --> 00:56:29.439
can the medical writer write the paper template

00:56:29.439 --> 00:56:32.239
and I fill in the values as a biostatistician?

00:56:32.239 --> 00:56:34.679
Do you think it would bring efficiency and traceability

00:56:34.679 --> 00:56:37.800
for manuscript production or any other comments?

00:56:37.800 --> 00:56:40.080
I think this should be quite feasible.

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:43.000
I think we go back to the question of what tooling

00:56:43.199 --> 00:56:45.919
would your medical writer be using?

00:56:45.919 --> 00:56:49.639
Particularly if they are willing to edit a QMD file

00:56:49.639 --> 00:56:52.320
to begin with, they can write all of the narrative.

00:56:52.320 --> 00:56:55.199
I can imagine wherever we had inline code,

00:56:56.159 --> 00:56:58.919
they could put blanks and maybe leave you a note saying,

00:56:58.919 --> 00:57:01.520
this is what number would go in here.

00:57:01.520 --> 00:57:03.120
And then maybe some placeholders

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:05.520
for this is what figure would go here.

00:57:05.520 --> 00:57:08.280
And then all you need to do is sort of grab that

00:57:08.280 --> 00:57:10.040
and in a way, fill in the blanks.

00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:12.679
Fill in the blanks with a lot of work, a lot of code

00:57:13.360 --> 00:57:15.840
that generates the figures and sort of tables

00:57:15.840 --> 00:57:18.760
that you are creating, but they can do that.

00:57:18.760 --> 00:57:21.600
I can also imagine if this is a person

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:23.800
you work with regularly and you develop

00:57:23.800 --> 00:57:26.439
sort of a particular workflow,

00:57:26.439 --> 00:57:30.280
you can decide this is how we will always label figures.

00:57:30.280 --> 00:57:33.199
This is how we will always label tables.

00:57:33.199 --> 00:57:37.080
And in a way they could almost write the cross references

00:57:37.080 --> 00:57:39.919
to your figures before you even write the code

00:57:39.919 --> 00:57:43.120
to produce them because ultimately all you need to do

00:57:43.120 --> 00:57:46.040
is to grab that same label from the cross reference

00:57:46.040 --> 00:57:47.760
and use it in your code cell.

