00:58:30.800 --> 00:58:33.120
and I will come back to this in a second.

00:58:34.120 --> 00:58:38.120
All right, so another question asks,

00:58:39.719 --> 00:58:44.719
so the QMD binder versioning replaces packages such as RM?

00:58:45.479 --> 00:58:46.719
Not necessarily.

00:58:46.719 --> 00:58:49.280
So there's still a place for RM here.

00:58:49.280 --> 00:58:53.399
RM would be useful for, for example,

00:58:53.399 --> 00:58:57.840
if you are using a,

00:58:57.840 --> 00:59:00.000
if you're collaborating with somebody else,

00:59:00.040 --> 00:59:01.520
if you're collaborating with somebody else,

00:59:01.520 --> 00:59:05.679
having RM activated on that project would mean that

00:59:05.679 --> 00:59:08.120
when you sort of pull the changes

00:59:08.120 --> 00:59:09.560
and you start writing things

00:59:09.560 --> 00:59:12.719
and you're sort of working in that RStudio project,

00:59:12.719 --> 00:59:15.679
you're using a certain version of those packages.

00:59:15.679 --> 00:59:17.879
And if you update any one of those packages,

00:59:17.879 --> 00:59:21.399
say there's a new functionality you wanna be able to use

00:59:21.399 --> 00:59:24.239
and you update the log file that goes with it

00:59:24.239 --> 00:59:25.679
and push your changes,

00:59:25.679 --> 00:59:27.679
your collaborator can now pull

00:59:27.679 --> 00:59:30.520
and next time they are working on the document,

00:59:30.520 --> 00:59:33.120
they're going to be using the right versions,

00:59:33.120 --> 00:59:36.280
the same versions as you are for your packages as well.

00:59:36.280 --> 00:59:40.959
What binder allows us to do is not two people necessarily

00:59:40.959 --> 00:59:44.879
both authoring code locally in something like RStudio,

00:59:44.879 --> 00:59:47.000
but creating a virtual environment

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:49.719
where someone might write the code.

00:59:49.719 --> 00:59:52.840
It's entirely possible that something like binder

00:59:52.840 --> 00:59:57.520
could be a essential component of your collaboration

00:59:58.199 --> 00:59:59.120
as well, personally for me,

00:59:59.120 --> 01:00:01.320
that's not something I've used before.

01:00:01.320 --> 01:00:04.280
That's not to say it's wrong in any way.

01:00:04.280 --> 01:00:07.199
But what I do like about something like binder,

01:00:07.199 --> 01:00:12.040
this virtual environment is for sort of the passive,

01:00:12.040 --> 01:00:13.959
for the audience of your paper,

01:00:13.959 --> 01:00:17.520
the reader of this paper who might be doing it passively,

01:00:17.520 --> 01:00:20.600
it provides a great way of being able to be like,

01:00:20.600 --> 01:00:23.199
let me just take a look to see how they made this figure.

01:00:23.199 --> 01:00:24.840
What if I change this a little bit?

01:00:24.840 --> 01:00:26.000
What would that look like?

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:29.040
So I think it's useful for that experimentation.

01:00:29.040 --> 01:00:32.719
I've personally not used a virtual environment as such

01:00:32.719 --> 01:00:36.800
for like actual development of the manuscript, if you will,

01:00:36.800 --> 01:00:38.959
but it could be as well.

